<paragraph blockId="12.[189,1399,1893,2027]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The largest member of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1905" box="[517,613,1893,1919]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Callipia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balteata">
<emphasis box="[517,613,1893,1919]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">balteata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, patterns strikingly contrasting, colour of the bands on the forewing upperside distinctly pink, and not red-brown as in the related species. The uncus is broader than in the other species. COI-barcode: the observed distance to the genetically most similar species (
<taxonomicName authority="Brehm, 2018" authorityName="Brehm" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,306,2001,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Callipia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jakobi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,306,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">C. jakobi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[314,406,2001,2027]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) is 6.0%.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
